04761nam a22007695i 9780226630038DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020018418  a97802266300387 a10.7208/97802266300382doi  a(DE-B1597)571686  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aGV1469.17.S63bJ34 2020 4aGV1469.17.S63 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a794.8qLOC1 aJagoda, Patrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aExperimental Games :bCritique, Play, and Design in the Age of Gamification /cPatrick Jagoda. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b46 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tPrologue: Game Experiments -- tPart I Framework -- tIntroduction: Society of the Game -- t1 Gamification -- t2 Experimentation -- tPart II Concepts -- t3 Choice -- t4 Control -- t5 Difficulty -- t6 Failure -- tPart III Design -- t7 Improvisation -- tCoda: Joy -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tLudography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn our unprecedentedly networked world, games have come to occupy an important space in many of our everyday lives. Digital games alone engage an estimated 2.5 billion people worldwide as of 2020, and other forms of gaming, such as board games, role playing, escape rooms, and puzzles, command an ever-expanding audience. At the same time, “gamification”—the application of game mechanics to traditionally nongame spheres, such as personal health and fitness, shopping, habit tracking, and more—has imposed unprecedented levels of competition, repetition, and quantification on daily life. Drawing from his own experience as a game designer, Patrick Jagoda argues that games need not be synonymous with gamification. He studies experimental games that intervene in the neoliberal project from the inside out, examining a broad variety of mainstream and independent games, including StarCraft, Candy Crush Saga, Stardew Valley, Dys4ia, Braid, and Undertale. Beyond a diagnosis of gamification, Jagoda imagines ways that games can be experimental—not only in the sense of problem solving, but also the more nuanced notion of problem making that embraces the complexities of our digital present. The result is a game-changing book on the sociopolitical potential of this form of mass entertainment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aComputer gamesxSocial aspects. 0aComputer games. 0aDigital computer simulation. 0aGamification. 0aVideo gamesxSocial aspects. 0aVideo games. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  adesign.  adigital media.  aeconomics.  aexperiment.  agames.  agamification.  amedia theory.  aneoliberalism.  aplay.  avideo games.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226630038423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226630038.jpg  a978-3-11-069309-6  UChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-SEWb2020